# Line endings are a portability bug, and this file is the fix.
#
# Found the hard way. The portability matrix asserts that local Spark, Docker,
# Kubernetes and Databricks all produce the same output hash from the same task. They
# did not — Databricks came back with a completely different fingerprint.
#
# The pipeline was fine. The DATA was not.
#
# CI checks the repo out on Linux and gets LF. A Databricks bundle uploads files from
# whatever is in the developer's working tree — and on Windows, git's autocrlf had
# rewritten the corpus to CRLF. Same six files, seven extra bytes each, a different
# sha2() of the text, a different doc_id, a different hash. Nothing errored. The
# pipeline just quietly ingested different bytes on one platform.
#
# Normalise everything to LF, in the repo and in every working tree. Shell scripts and
# Docker entrypoints need this anyway: a CRLF `run.sh` fails inside a container with
# the wonderfully unhelpful `bad interpreter: /usr/bin/env bash^M: no such file`.
* text=auto eol=lf

# The corpus is the input to a content-addressed hash. Its bytes ARE the test.
*.txt text eol=lf

# Never let git touch these.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.parquet binary
*.joblib binary
